{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486997"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:53:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:53:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"227"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"227","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/227"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.67,0.11,0.11,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"227"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102431"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"227","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/227"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"227"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84905"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6563"},{"type":"tags","id":"6630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11106"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11313"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35441"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42033"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102431"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic for a routine health check. He has a medical history significant for hypertension, diabetes mellitus, and stage 3 chronic kidney disease (CKD). His medications include amlodipine, atenolol, furosemide, calcium carbonate, cholecalciferol, gliclazide, atorvastatin and pregabalin. He is an active smoker with a 55 pack year history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 145/75 mmHg. Cardiorespiratory exam finds a soft right-sided carotid bruit, but no other abnormal physical findings. Duplex ultrasonography shows a 50 % stenosis with no plaque ulceration. His blood investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFasting plasma glucose level: 5.7 mmol/L (3.9 - 5.6)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHbA1c: 3.9 % (4.0 - 6.6)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal cholesterol: 11.1 mmol/L (\u003C5.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELDL cholesterol: 5.6 mmol/L (\u003C3.4)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHDL cholesterol: 3.3 mmol/L (\u003E1.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR: 43 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2 \u003C/sup\u003E(\u003E90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carotid stent placement","Aspirin","Rivaroxaban","Carotid endarterectomy","CT scan of the brain"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, a 70-year-old male smoker with hypertension, diabetes mellitus, and stage 3 CKD presents with asymptomatic carotid artery stenosis. Blood tests show abnormal lipid profile and renal function. Management involves initiating \u003Cstrong\u003Easpirin\u003C/strong\u003E therapy, which is standard for asymptomatic carotid stenosis in patients with cardiovascular risk factors. Other priorities include addressing CVD risk factors like smoking cessation, blood pressure, cholesterol, and diabetes control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELow-dose aspirin (75-150 mg daily) is generally considered safe in patients with CKD, including this patient with stage 3 CKD. While high-dose aspirin can potentially worsen renal function through inhibition of prostaglandin synthesis, low-dose aspirin has minimal effects on renal hemodynamics. The cardiovascular benefits of aspirin in this high-risk patient with carotid stenosis outweigh the small risk of renal effects. Regular monitoring of renal function is still recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid stent placement\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved for symptomatic or severe asymptomatic stenosis (\u003E70-80 %), especially in patients with difficult neck anatomy or high surgical risk due to comorbidities and age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid endarterectomy\u003C/strong\u003E, the gold standard treatment, for symptomatic stenosis (\u003E50 %) with TIAs or strokes, is typically favoured in younger patients with longer life expectancy, favourable neck anatomy and low perioperative risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERivaroxaban\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003ECT brain scan\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated for asymptomatic carotid stenosis without neurological symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Asymptomatic carotid artery stenosis of \u003C50 % stenosis can be treated with anti-platelets and risk factor modification alone."],"references":["Hackam DG. Optimal Medical Management of Asymptomatic Carotid Stenosis. Stroke. 2021;52(6):2191\u20138. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33947208/","Arasu R, Arasu A, Muller J. Carotid artery stenosis: An approach to its diagnosis and management. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2021;50:821-5. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2021/november/carotid-artery-stenosis","Adla T, Adlova R. Multimodality Imaging of Carotid Stenosis. Int J Angiol. 2015 Sep;24(3):179-84. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4572013/","Louridas G, Junaid A. Management of carotid artery stenosis. Update for family physicians.\u00a0Can Fam Physician. 2005;51(7):984-989. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1479527/","Narins CR, Illig KA. Patient selection for carotid stenting versus endarterectomy: a systematic review. J Vasc Surg. 2006;44(3):661-72. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16950453/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84905"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"227"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84905"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-12T17:40:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-12T17:41:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"227"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102431"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"typ